A .env (environment) file stores sensitive configuration values inside this we find so much senstive data like : Database Credentials
                                                                                                                AWS / Cloud Credentials
                                                                                                                Email / SMTP Credentials
                                                                                                                 Application Secrets



                                  
                                                                   
                                                                          Google Dork To Find .env Files 




filetype:env "DB_PASSWORD="
filetype:env "DB_USERNAME="
filetype:env "DB_HOST="
filetype:env "APP_KEY="
filetype:env "APP_ENV="
filetype:env "APP_DEBUG="
filetype:env "API_KEY="
filetype:env "SECRET_KEY="
filetype:env "AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY="
filetype:env "AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="
filetype:env "MAIL_PASSWORD="
filetype:env "MAIL_USERNAME="
intitle:"index of" ".env"
filetype:env ".env.local"
filetype:env ".env.dev"
filetype:env ".env.prod"
filetype:env ".env.backup"
filetype:env ".env.old"
inurl:/.env
inurl:/config/.env
inurl:/public/.env




                                                                                      CVSS Score

CVSS v3.1 Base Score: 9.8 â€“ Critical | P1






                                                                                        Impact



If a .env file is exposed, an attacker can: Obtain database usernames and passwords
                                            Access or modify entire databases
                                            Steal AWS / cloud credentials
                                             Abuse SMTP credentials to send phishing emails
                                            Extract application secret keys
                                            Forge sessions or JWT tokens
                                           Bypass authentication mechanisms
                                           Achieve full application and infrastructure compromise
                                          Cause financial loss and data breaches
                                          Damage brand reputation and compliance posture





                                                                                     Remediation



Immediately block public access to .env files at the web server level
Move .env files outside the web root
Add .env to .gitignore to prevent repository exposure

Rotate all exposed credentials immediately: Database passwords
                                           AWS keys
                                            SMTP credentials
                                            API tokens

Use secure secret management: Environment variables (server-side)
                              Vault services (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault)

Enable monitoring for unusual access or abuse
Perform a full incident response review
